Inferences:¶

  1. Readmissing Count
    • Most patients get readmitted to the hospital only 1 other time. This could imply that either the patients admitted are not with very serious injuries/diseases or hospital care is very good that readmissions of patients are not necessary. It could also mean that patients are not happy with the care and they go to another hospital.
    • There are very few patients that need to be readmitted more number of times.
  2. Gender
    • There are more female patients than there are male patients
  3. Numerical Features: BMI, ABG and Pulse rate
    • There are 3 features BMI, ABG and Pulse that have no skew. There distribution is mostly normal with majority of the data situated around the mean.
    • Post patients have their BMI, ABG and Pulse levels normal.
  4. Secondary Diagnosis
    • There are very few patients that don't have a secondary diagnosis. Most patients that are present in the data have atleast one other disease in addition to the reason they got admitted to this hospital.

Inferences:¶

  1. Gender - Length of Stay

    • Most male patients have a shorter length of stay than female patients

  2. Readmission Count - Length of Stay

    • Patients that get readmitted one other time stay longer in the hospital than those that get readmitted multiple times.

  3. BMI - Length of Stay

    • Patients with lower BMI generally have a shorter stay than those with a higher BMI
    • There are a few patients that have a normal BMI but their length of stay is very long. This could mean that they have some health condition not affecting their weight
    • There are overweight and underweight patients having a short length of stay.
    • But, overall there is no correlation between BMI and the length of stay

  4. Pulse rate - Length of Stay

    • Pulse rate and length of stay also has no correlation. As there is no specific trend visible in the data
    • This feature has more anomalies than the analysis betwenn BMI and length of stay.

  5. Secondary Diagnosis - Length of Stay

    • There is a gradual trend visible in this analysis. As with increasing number of secondary diagnosis there is an increase in the length of stay. This means that these 2 featurs could be strongly correlated.
    • Patients with no secondary diagnosis have a larger length of stay than those having multiple health conditions. This exhibits a bit different behaviour as compared to above trend. These patients could be having a very complex primary diagnosis or having treatment challenges or any other reasons.

4.1 OLS MODEL 1¶

In [ ]:
data_enc = pd.get_dummies(data,columns = data.select_dtypes(include='object').columns.tolist())    # Encoding

target_column = 'LengthOfStay'
X = data_enc.drop(['LengthOfStay'],axis = 1)              # independent features
y = data_enc['LengthOfStay']                          # dependent variable

# Input data is split into Training and Testing data - based on random_state=1000 (Optimal value identified through Trail & Error)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=1000)
In [ ]:
# Scaling is done after train test split to prevent data leakage
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_sc = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_sc = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Train the linear regression model and fitting to data
model1 = LinearRegression()
model1.fit(X_train_sc, y_train)

y_pred_train = model1.predict(X_train_sc)     # Predicting using train data set 
y_pred_test = model1.predict(X_test_sc)       # Predicting using test data set 

print(f'MSE of model on training data: {mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred_train)}')
print(f"R Squared on training data: {r2_score(y_train, y_pred_train)}")
print()
print(f'MSE of model on testing data: {mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_test)}')
print(f"R Squared on testing data: {r2_score(y_test, y_pred_test)}")
print()
print(f'Coefficients: {model1.coef_}')
print()
print(f'Intercepts: {model1.intercept_}')

  • This model gives a low error for both training and testing data. But the R Squared value is not that high for either case. Only 68% of the variance in the target variable is explained by the independent features in the model when we use testing data. And only 62% of the variance of target is explained by independedent features of the training data.

#### Replace Outliers with Upper and lower limit 

# Function to replace outliers with upper and lower limits
def replace_outliers_with_limits(column):
    Q1 = column.quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = column.quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_limit = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_limit = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    column = column.apply(lambda x: upper_limit if x > upper_limit else lower_limit if x < lower_limit else x)
    return column

# Replace outliers with upper and lower limits
data['Pulse'] = replace_outliers_with_limits(data['Pulse'])
data['BMI'] = replace_outliers_with_limits(data['BMI'])
data['ABG'] = replace_outliers_with_limits(data['ABG'])

# How many records that are outliers in below features
Q1 = data['BMI'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = data['BMI'].quantile(0.75)
lower_limit = Q1 - 1.5 * (Q3 - Q1)
upper_limit = Q3 + 1.5 * (Q3 - Q1)

print('Number of records with BMI outliers are :', data[(data['BMI'] < lower_limit) | (data['BMI'] > upper_limit)].shape[0])
# data[(data['BMI'] < lower_limit) | (data['BMI'] > upper_limit)]

Q1 = data['ABG'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = data['ABG'].quantile(0.75)
lower_limit = Q1 - 1.5 * (Q3 - Q1)
upper_limit = Q3 + 1.5 * (Q3 - Q1)

print('Number of records with ABG outliers are :', data[(data['ABG'] < lower_limit) | (data['ABG'] > upper_limit)].shape[0])
